 class="post h-entry"><div class="containbox" style="margin:auto; position:relative; margin-top: 20px; margin-bottom:20px; width:98%; background-color:var(--background-color);"><div style="float:left;"><a href="/about" class="p-author"><img class="ppic" src="https://shellsharks-images.s3.amazonaws.com/surfshark.png" width="60" alt="author-image" ></a></div><div style="float:left;"><span id="author" style="font-weight:bold;">Mike Sass</span><br><span id="handle" style="color:var(--light-font-color);">@shellsharks</span></div><div style="float:right;padding:10px 0px 0px 0px;"><i class="ph ph-calendar-dot"></i> <span id="date" style="font-size:0.75em;" class="dt-published">11/22/23 22:28</span></div><br><br><br><header id="header" class="post-header"></header><div class="post-content e-content"><div class="containbox">Update: <a href="https://apps.apple.com/us/app/delta-game-emulator/id1048524688">Delta</a> is <a href="https://9to5mac.com/2024/04/17/riley-testut-launches-delta-game-emulator-on-app-store-for-everyone-altstore-marketplace-for-eu/">now available</a> natively on iOS/iPadOS!</div><p><br /><p>I‚Äôve always considered myself a ‚Äúgamer‚Äù. But I like to think there are (<em>at least</em>) two types of ‚Äúhardcore‚Äù gamers - those that play alot but only a few titles and those that like to play alot and play <em>everything</em>. I‚Äôm more the <em>former</em>. I grew up in the 90‚Äôs, so my love for gaming is shaped by consoles like the classic Nintendo, Super Nintendo, N64 and GameCube (I was <em>clearly</em> a Nintendo kid). I‚Äôve documented some of my <a href="/notes/2011/07/07/favorite-nintendo-games">favorite titles here</a>. In those days, I actually played quite a few different games. Starting with the GameCube, I became much more of a mono-player, in other words, I really just played one game on whatever was the latest console. With the GameCube I literally <em>only</em> played Super Smash, on Xbox it was Halo, with Xbox 360 more Halo and on Xbox One it was Destiny. (Somewhere in there I played a fair bit of Star Wars: Battlefront). As much as I miss the early days of Halo, LAN parties and the <a href="https://halo.fandom.com/wiki/Noob_Combo">plasma pistol + battle rifle combo</a>, nothing comes quite as close to the ‚Äúgolden days‚Äù of gaming nostalgia as playing those NES/SNES/N64 games. Though I will never be able to recapture what it felt like to be a kid with no other responsibilities playing games with my brother early on a weekend morning, I still love to play these old games.<p>I have kept the consoles and games from my youth and <em>have</em> actually played them pretty recently (especially during the early days of the pandemic) and they‚Äôve worked great! One issue with that experience is that playing classic games on modern high-definition TVs makes for a bit of an eye sore. It also isn‚Äôt the most portable experience. Enter emulators. I‚Äôve played retro games on emulators for a long time now but there‚Äôs never been a great option for iOS outside of the <a href="https://www.theiphonewiki.com/wiki/Jailbreak">jailbreak</a> scene. <strong><a href="https://deltaemulatorapp.com">Delta</a></strong> is an emulator from <a href="https://github.com/rileytestut">Riley Testut</a> (of former <a href="http://www.gba4iosapp.com">GBA4iOS</a> fame) that I‚Äôve recently installed on my iPad so that I can once again enjoy these classic titles! Installing it is <em>fairly</em> straight forward and a really quick operation. The <a href="https://faq.altstore.io">instructions can be found here</a>. It requires sideloading the app through an alternative app store, <a href="https://altstore.io">AltStore</a>. AltStore has some other interesting apps that I will be interested in checking out in the future. Also interesting, <a href="https://www.apple.com/privacy/docs/Building_a_Trusted_Ecosystem_for_Millions_of_Apps_A_Threat_Analysis_of_Sideloading.pdf">given Apples historical stance</a>, is recent news around <a href="https://www.theverge.com/2023/11/12/23957560/sideloading-and-other-changes-are-coming-to-ios-in-the-eu-soon">Apple allowing sideloading</a> in a near-future iOS release.<p>Once installed, Delta is easy enough to navigate - mostly, you just need to import your roms. There is some <a href="https://www.kotaku.com.au/2021/10/in-defense-of-roms-a-solution-to-dying-games-and-broken-copyright-laws/">nuanced legality</a> to how you acquire these roms and though there is not much history of enforcement, you should be conscious of how/what you are downloading. Also be careful of rom sites as they have been known to <a href="https://www.vintageisthenewold.com/game-pedia/can-game-roms-have-virus">distribute compromised files</a>.<p>Playing games is a great experience on iPad. Resizable window(s) (<em>using stage manager</em>), external controller support, save states, game library, etc‚Ä¶ All right on your iPad. <em>Amazing</em>! So far, I‚Äôve done a full 100% play through of Super Mario World (the GOAT Mario game) and have started a replay of Super Mario RPG (which Nintendo just dropped the <a href="https://www.nintendo.com/us/store/products/super-mario-rpg-switch/">redux</a> of). I think for now I‚Äôll finish another playthrough of the classic and then pick up the new version sometime in the future, especially if they add a hard mode or new gameplay.<p>So if you‚Äôre looking to do some retro gaming, check out Delta for iOS/iPadOS!</div><div style="bottom:-5px; text-align:right;font-size:0.75em;"><i class="ph ph-pencil"></i> 601</div><hr style="opacity:35%;margin-top: 10px;margin-bottom: 10px;width:75%;"><div id="info" class="wrapper"><div class="box 1" style="background-color:var(--background-color);"><div><i class="ph ph-note-pencil"></i> <span id="updated" style="font-size:0.75em;">4/19/24 10:05</span></div><div><i class="ph ph-map-pin-area" title="Posted from"></i> <span id="posted-from" style="font-size:0.75em;">iPad Pro</span></div><div><i class="ph ph-game-controller"></i> <span id="comment" style="font-size:0.75em;">Super Mario RPG</span></div></div><div class="box2" style="bottom:0;"><div style="text-align:right; padding:5px 5px 5px 5px;"><a class="u-url" href=""><i class="ph ph-link" title="Permalink"></i></a> <a href="/notebook"><i class="ph ph-book-open" title="Notebook"></i></a> <a href="/"><i class="ph ph-house" title="Home"></i></a></div><div style="font-size:0.75em;color:var(--light-font-color);padding:5px 5px 0px 5px;text-align:right;"><i class="ph ph-tag"></i> <span id="tags" style="padding:0px 3px 0px 3px;"><a href="/tags?tag=nablopomo">#nablopomo</a></span> <span id="tags" style="padding:0px 3px 0px 3px;"><a href="/tags?tag=life">#life</a></span> <span id="tags" style="padding:0px 3px 0px 3px;"><a href="/tags?tag=gaming">#gaming</a></span> <span id="tags" style="padding:0px 3px 0px 3px;"><a href="/tags?tag=nintendo">#nintendo</a></span></div></div></div></div></article><div style="margin-bottom:20px; margin-right:5px; margin-left:5px;"> <a class="prev" style="margin-right: 2em; margin-left:8px;" href="/notes/2023/11/22/two-things-to-know-about-yaml#title">&laquo; Two things to know about YAML</a><div style="float:right;"><a class="next" href="/notes/2023/11/24/how-to-spend-my-time-off#title" style="margin-right: 8px;">How to spend my time off &raquo;</a></div></div><style> .wrapper { display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; } img {max-width:100%}</style></div></main><aside class="container_item"></aside><footer class="container_item"> <center><span style="color:var(--light-font-color); font-size:.8em; font-style:italic; position:relative; top:25px;">Brought to you with <i class="ph-fill ph-heart-straight" style="color:var(--accent-color);"></i> by <a href="https://shellsharks.com/about">Shellsharks</a></span></center> <center> <img id="sharkfooter" src="/assets/img/sharks-circling.png" alt="Circling Sharks" style="width:150px;"></img> </center></footer></div><noscript><div class="panel" align="center" style="font